 1. ESP32 + I2C LCD (16x2 with I2C module)
LCD Pins → ESP32
LCD Pin	Connect to ESP32
VCC	5V
GND	GND
SDA	GPIO 21
SCL	GPIO 22
Notes:
Use 0x27 or 0x3F address (you already used 0x27 )
If display not working → run I2C scanner
Keep wires short to avoid garbage text

2. Buzzer with BC547 Transistor
Since you're using a transistor, this is the correct safe connection

Components:
BC547 Transistor
1kΩ resistor
Buzzer
Connections:
Component	Connection
ESP32 GPIO 27	→ 1k resistor → Base (BC547)
Emitter (BC547)	GND
Collector (BC547)	Negative (-) of buzzer
Positive (+) of buzzer	3.3V or 5V
Working:
ESP32 sends signal → transistor amplifies → buzzer sounds louder

3. LED Connection
Components:
LED
220Ω resistor (important)
Connections:
LED Pin	Connection
Anode (+, long leg)	GPIO 2
Cathode (-, short leg)	→ 220Ω resistor → GND
 Important:
Always use resistor or LED may burn

4. ESP32 Power
ESP32 Pin	Connection
VIN / 5V	5V supply (USB or adapter)
GND	Common Ground

5. Common Ground (VERY IMPORTANT)
All GND must be connected together:

ESP32 GND
LCD GND
Transistor emitter
LED resistor GND
Without common ground, circuit will not work properly.

 Complete Wiring Overview
ESP32
 ├── GPIO 21 → LCD SDA
 ├── GPIO 22 → LCD SCL
 ├── GPIO 2  → LED (+) → resistor → GND
 ├── GPIO 27 → resistor → BC547 Base
 │
 ├── BC547:
 │     Collector → Buzzer (-)
 │     Emitter → GND
 │
 ├── Buzzer (+) → 5V
 ├── LCD VCC → 5V
 ├── LCD GND → GND

 Troubleshooting Tips
Garbage text on LCD:
Add delay after lcd.init()
Use Wire.setClock(100000); (you already did )
Check loose wires
Adjust contrast screw on I2C module

Buzzer not working:
Check transistor direction (flat side matters)
Try active buzzer first
Ensure correct GPIO (27)

LED not glowing:
Reverse polarity
Check resistor connection
